What is a Medical Bioresorbable Polymer and Material?
A Medical Bioresorbable Polymer and Material is an advanced biomaterial engineered to safely degrade and be naturally absorbed by the human body after fulfilling its intended medical function. These materials are widely used in temporary implants, absorbable sutures, orthopedic fixation devices, cardiovascular stents, tissue engineering scaffolds, and controlled drug delivery systems, eliminating the need for secondary implant removal surgeries while promoting natural healing.

Modern medical bioresorbable polymers and materials integrate advanced technologies including:

· Polylactic Acid (PLA) for orthopedic implants and surgical fixation

· Polyglycolic Acid (PGA) for absorbable sutures and biodegradable medical devices

· Polycaprolactone (PCL) for long-term controlled drug delivery applications

· Polysaccharide-based Biomaterials for regenerative medicine and tissue engineering

· Smart Biodegradable Polymers with programmable degradation profiles

· Advanced Drug Delivery Platforms for targeted and sustained therapeutic release

By providing temporary structural support while gradually degrading inside the body, medical bioresorbable materials help eliminate secondary surgeries, reduce post-operative complications, improve patient recovery, and accelerate the development of next-generation regenerative therapies.

